Call or order online by 3pm the day of!

shared_text:
Elk Point-Jefferson Music Boosters
May 12 at 10:32 AM ·

Congratulations to Kelsie Olson, for being our National Choral School Award Winner. Kelsie has been in choir and show choir for 4 years, and was voted show choir president this year. She has participated in All-State Chorus, and has performed solos and groups pieces throughout the years. Kelsie was our featured ballad soloist for show choir this year, and was AMAZING. This award is in recognition of singular merit, ability, and achievement, of outstanding contributions to the success of the school vocal program, and of an unusual degree of loyalty, co-operation and high qualities of conduct Kelsie, you will be missed. Thank you for your leadership all these years!!

Congratulations to Matthew Giorgio on being named the Louis Armstrong Award winner for the 2019-20 school year. He has been an exceptional student to work with over his 4 years and played guitar as a freshman and sophomore, played drumset his junior year when we were in need and returned to guitar for his senior year. May 14 at 12:18 PM ·

Congratulations to Kacie Stepp, for being named the 2020 Choir Spirit Award winner! Kacie has been involved in choir for 7 years, show choir 4, the last 2 as Dance Captain, and has been a flag girl for marching band for three years as well. This award is given in recognition of the enthusiasm, spirit, energy, and the positive attitude necessary for the overall success of the choir program. Kacie will be missed as a musician, but even more, as an amazing human. Thank you for everything, Kacie.

The Elk Point-Jefferson School District will continue with our at-home learning for the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year. The district is looking at the possibility of completing kindergarten screening this spring as well as the possibility of providing some supports for special education students. These have not been finalized at this time. Anything that we do will be done within CDC guidelines and recommendations to ensure everyone’s safety. Thank you for your continued support and hard work this school year.

Jordan Niles is a Senior at EPJ and his dad is a physician assistant in a family practice clinic in Iowa. Covid 19 and recent protocols require he and his staff to wear personal protective equipment all day everyday! Jordan has been dedicated to getting this thing up and running so he can start making straps for N95 masks because the elastic is hurting the back of people’s ears. Because of what he learned in his Intro to Tech Class, he was able to accomplish this task! #ShowingPrideTakingAction

post_text:
From Superintendent Barrios:
With the Governor closing schools for the remainder of the year, we are having to adjust everything that we do as a school district. Knowing this, the 2020 Graduation Ceremony will be something that needs to be adjusted. We will not be able to hold the graduation ceremony on the scheduled date inside the school, so school administration and the School Board Curriculum Committee (Sabrina Sayler and Cherie Noteboom) will meet this week to discuss possible options and then present a recommendation to the entire school board on Monday, April 13th, at the regularly scheduled board meeting. A reminder that this meeting will be held over Zoom. A link will be provided when our board agenda is released later this week. Thank you for your patience with all of this and understand that we plan to provide a solution that still makes this memorable for our graduating seniors.

SCHOOL LUNCHES

Please complete school lunch surveys by Tuesdays at 8:00am for the week.
April 6-9 lunches will be available to pick-up/delivered every day that week. April 9th you will receive lunch for April 10th as well because of Good Friday.
After Easter, we will be handing out meals two days at a time to reduce the number of interactions. For example, handing out on a Monday for both Monday and Tuesday of a week.

For those interested, a message from the State DOE:
Responding to the need for educational resources, SDPB’s WORLD Channel will begin broadcasting At Home Learning programs for grades 6-12 on Monday, March 30, on SDPB2-TV. Schedule will be: M-F 11 a.m.-4 p.m. Central / 10 a.m.-3 p.m. Mountain. These are daily, free over-the-air broadcasts featuring science, history and other educational programming. This At-Home Learning block has been curated and supplemented to include related assets from the PBS LearningMedia website, a free online service of thousands of educational resources: https://www.pbslearningmedia.org/

https://www.sdpb.org/learn/learnersconnection/ provides free resources for at-home learning for families with children from pre-K through high school.

We received word today that South Dakota school will not be in session for another week, March 23rd-27th. The state has asked that we work to provide flex, or alternate, education to our students. Our administration and teaching staff have been in the process of developing a plan for our district this week. We will have additional information regarding our district plans by the end of this week. This plan will be able to be implemented for the next week or longer if need be.
We will still plan to provide sack lunches for those who need them. I will send out another survey to see who needs them. These will be FREE lunches to ANY enrolled EPJ students.
We know that we have many different needs to meet with our students, and we working hard to ensure that we do so. We ask for your patience as we navigate through this.

post_text:
Sack Lunch and Backpack Program UPDATE!!

Reminder, if you signed up for sack lunches these next two days to please pick them up. They are located at the Middle School door on the bus loop at the school in Elk Point and Jefferson City Hall from 11:15-12:15. If you need them delivered please call the High School Office (356-5900) and let us know.

Also, those that receive the Backpack Bags of food from the Backpack Program will be available for pick up at the food pantry Thursday from 10:00am-12:00pm and 4:00pm-6:00pm.

Our administrative team continues to be in contact with the State Dept. Health and Dept. of Education. We are also discussing what can be done if we remain out of school for a longer amount of time. We will share information as we are able to.

Thank you for your patience and understanding as we are all learning how to deal with a situation such as this. We have many school employees and volunteers that are working hard to help our school families and community navigate this situation. We thank everyone for their help.

#ShowingPrideTakingAction

The Elk Point-Jefferson School district has been working with our lunch service provider to provide free sack lunches for children who may need them these next few days before our scheduled Spring Break. Because this was such an immediate, out of the ordinary event, our provider does not currently have the food to get lunches ready for Monday but may be able to for Tuesday and Wednesday. Mr. Barrios is working to get sandwich stuff to put together sack lunches for Monday though.
To get an idea of how many lunches we will need to get put together, we ask that you complete this short anonymous survey to give us a count. The survey also asks where you would like to pick up the lunches. You can pick them up at the middle school doors by the bus loop at the school, or you can pick them up at Jefferson City Hall. The lunches will be available from 11:15-12:15 at both locations.

post_text: Elk Point-Jefferson Schools will be closed March 16th – March 20th as suggested by Governor Noem. School buildings will be closed beginning today, March 13th at 5:00pm. There will be no use of the facilities by any outside organizations or groups until further notice. All school staff will be asked not to report to school during this time. Custodial staff will continue to clean and disinfect throughout the buildings. The district will release additional relevant information as it is provided to us.

post_text:
The Elk Point-Jefferson School district is aware of the Coronavirus (COVID-19) and its continuous spread
both nationally and internationally. We can assure you, as a District, we are taking the necessary steps
to be as prepared as possible in the event that our community and school would be impacted. We are in
constant contact with the South Dakota Department of Health, the local County Emergency Managers,
the South Dakota Department of Education and the South Dakota School Superintendents Association to
stay on top of the situation. As we are made aware of information that pertains to our school
community, we will continue to keep our parents and public informed.
A reminder, for all types of sickness, that students should stay home until they are fever-free for 24
hours.
The Elk Point-Jefferson has put together a resource page regarding the Coronavirus (COIVD-19): https://www.epj.k12.sd.us/News/94#sthash.DRHsigI1.cgGRKVpG.dpbs

post_text: This morning the Elk Point-Jefferson school administration was made aware of a possible threat. Law enforcement was called immediately and Superintendent Barrios directed everyone to “Secure the Building”, also known as a “Soft Lockdown”. We were in this protocol for approximately 30 minutes. This meant that no one was allowed to enter or exit the school buildings and there was no outside recess. Students still went to classes and were free to move about inside the building. Once law enforcement informed us there was no longer a threat we resumed the day as normal.

post_text:
Throughout the school year, we are sharing different district reports regarding state testing, enrollments, college and career readiness, and other pertinent information.

This month we are sharing EPJ Graduate post-secondary plans and graduation rates.

86% of our 2019 graduates went on to some form of higher education. Whether it is a 2-year school, 4-year school, military service or workforce, our students leave ready to take it on.

93% of our students graduated on time (in 4 years) and 95% of our students completed high school.

Great things are happening at Elk Point-Jefferson!

#ShowingPrideTakingAction #HuskyPride

Mrs. Thompson’s first grade class has been working hard writing friendly letters. We started by writing to our families in our Friday journals each week. Then we practiced writing short notes to people within the school building. Lastly, we wrote (and rewrote) to someone we could mail a letter to. We learned all about punctuation, greetings, and how to address an envelope. We walked all the way to the Elk Point Post Office and back. Lots of sights along the way, we had so much fun!

shared_text:
Elk Point-Jefferson Elementary
January 10 at 4:28 PM ·

4th grade Language Arts-
Did you know that Dachshunds were originally bred to fight badgers? Or that a cow has no top teeth? How about that as a kid, Bob Ross once nursed an alligator back to health in his bathtub? 4th grade language arts students have learned these facts and more while researching this week. Research is just one of the many steps they will go through this quarter to create class books. Each class's book will be sent to a publishing company where it will be bound and made available for purchase. Stay tuned on our journey to becoming published authors!

post_text: Riverside Fareway in Sioux City has teamed up with the EPJ PTO for an amazing fundraiser. Fareway is going to give the school 1% back on all purchases made at their store now through the end of the school year. After shopping at Fareway turn your receipt into your child’s homeroom teacher, JK-5. Students in MS/HS can turn them into either office. The receipts will be tallied at the end of each month and the winning class will receive a prize from the PTO.

Once a month we will be sharing different district reports regarding state testing, enrollments, college and career readiness, and other pertinent information.

This month we are sharing our College and Career Readiness Scores from the South Dakota Department of Education.

As a district, 79% of our graduates were Coursework Ready, 75% of graduates were Assessment Ready, and 64% of graduates were College and Career Ready. Meaning they were both Coursework ready and Assessment Ready. The State average is 48% of students College and Career Ready.

Great things are happening at Elk Point-Jefferson!
The graphic below shows how students can become Coursework Ready and Assessment Ready.

#ShowingPrideTakingAction #HuskyPride

EPJ Huskies Football
October 24, 2019 at 10:53 AM ·

A Free Will Offering for Trevor Zuehlke and his family, will be taken at halftime of the football game tonight. Trevor is the Britton-Hecla quarterback that was hit during last Friday night's football game against Warner. Trevor was airlifted to Avera Mckennan in Sioux Falls where he required emergency surgery to fix a brain bleed. Currently, Trevor remains in a medically-induced coma. Please bring some extra $$$ to the game and be watching for the donation buckets during half time.#FORTREV

post_text:
Once a month we will be sharing different district reports regarding state testing, enrollments, college and career readiness, and other pertinent information.

This month we are sharing our state testing results from this last spring. State testing happens every spring in grades 3-8 and 11th grade.

As a district, 68% of our students tested were proficient in ELA (2nd in the Dak XII), 55% proficient in Math (3rd in the Dak XII) and 60% proficient in science (1st in the Dak XII).

Great things happening and room for improvement as a district as well.
The graphic below shows how we compared to the state average as well.

#ShowingPrideTakingAction #HuskyPride

The school building is beginning to turn blue! Progress is slowed by high winds and cold, but we are getting closer. The first of two coats has been applied in many areas. The blue color will become more even with the second coat of blue cork material.
Thank you for your patience as this project is completed this fall.
